WEBVTT

00:02.100 --> 00:05.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Nashville
has long been considered
the beating heart of
the country music world,

00:05.633 --> 00:10.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but the new album "The Nashville
Sound" by Jason Isbell is
infusing the genre with rock,

00:11.600 --> 00:13.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
folk and blues.

00:13.700 --> 00:17.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Grammy Award winner has
turned heads with his lyrics,
which this time around address

00:17.800 --> 00:20.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
topics like poverty,
race, and love.

00:20.766 --> 00:25.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown recently joined
Isbell on the first stop
of his international tour.

00:27.666 --> 00:32.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In his song
"The Last of My Kind," Jason
Isbell creates a character based

00:38.533 --> 00:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on people he grew up around
in rural Northern Alabama who
fear how the world is changing.

00:48.266 --> 00:53.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JASON ISBELL, Musician: A lot
of people that I grew up with,
went to school with in Alabama,

00:56.466 --> 01:01.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a lot of people in my family
who told me growing up that
cities were terrible places

01:03.500 --> 01:07.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and anything outside of our
little circle was scary and
dangerous and frightening.

01:07.233 --> 01:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I thought about the effect
that had on people, when you
start to believe that, and

01:11.500 --> 01:16.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you let yourself be so afraid
of other people and the outside
world, that you never feel

01:16.500 --> 01:19.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
tethered, you never
feel a connection with
the rest of humanity.

01:19.466 --> 01:23.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I wrote that song
based on that kind of fear.

01:23.633 --> 01:28.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In both ballads
and hard-charging rock 'n' roll
songs like "Cumberland Gap,"

01:35.166 --> 01:39.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Isbell's storytelling prowess
has made him one of today's most
acclaimed singer-songwriters.

01:39.500 --> 01:44.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His last album, "ÑMDNMÑSomething
More Than Free," won two
Grammys and achieved the

01:45.933 --> 01:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rare feat of topping folk, rock,
and country charts in 2015.

01:55.266 --> 02:00.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now 38, he's back with a new
album titled "The Nashville
Sound," and we joined him and

02:02.300 --> 02:05.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his band, The 400 Unit, at
the Thomas Wolfe Auditorium in
Asheville, North Carolina, on

02:06.800 --> 02:11.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the first day of their
new national tour.

02:20.566 --> 02:25.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once again, Isbell's
songs are filled with
rural country characters,
this time also reflecting

02:26.733 --> 02:28.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
